	\begin{abstract}
		We present the Quantum Coherence Theory (QCT) model, a novel cosmological framework that structurally reformulates dark matter and the cosmological constant with scalar coherence fields derived directly from the Cosmic Microwave Background (CMB) temperature power spectrum. This framework interprets the CMB TT power spectrum as a resonance map encoding coherence delays and accelerations which manifest as large-scale structure inversion or enhancement across observational datasets. We construct three dimensionless fields \( \mu(z) \), \( \nu(z) \), and \( \phi(z) = \mu(z) - \nu(z) \), representing quantum coherence bursts, wells, and net field intensity, respectively. These fields are evaluated against several cosmological datasets (Pantheon+, KiDS, DR9Q, GWTC, BAO) using normalized RMS residuals, correlation coefficients, and visual overlays. We derive a Lagrangian for \( \phi(z) \) evolution including an echo kernel \( \kappa(z) \), modeled as a feedback mechanism coupling coherence bursts and gravitational wells. The model achieves strong RMS alignment and correlation with observational data, without parameter tuning.
	\end{abstract}
	
	\section{Introduction}
	Standard cosmology relies on the presence of cold dark matter (CDM) and a cosmological constant (\( \Lambda \)) to explain structure formation and acceleration. QCT instead models these phenomena as the result of quantum coherence memory seeded during recombination, encoded in the acoustic harmonics of the CMB TT spectrum. We build scalar fields from these harmonics and show their correlation with redshift-dependent observables. This work explores the guiding question: \textit{Can quantum coherence memory encoded in the early universe replace the need for dark matter and dark energy entirely?} We define \textit{quantum coherence memory} as persistent nonlocal structure encoded in scalar field harmonics originating from the CMB recombination epoch.
	
	\section{Coherence Field Construction}
	Let \( D_\ell^{TT} \) be the angular power spectrum of the CMB temperature anisotropies. Where, \( D_\ell^{TT} \) refers to the Planck 2018 temperature power spectrum (COM\_PowerSpect\_CMB-TT-full\_R3.01.txt), extracted without smoothing. Peak and trough identification is performed via a second derivative filter. 
	The Gaussian envelope width \( \lambda \) used in projecting each harmonic to redshift space is fixed across all datasets to preserve coherence structure scaling, though its interpretation may vary with redshift bin resolution. We define coherence peaks and troughs as the local maxima and minima of \( D_\ell^{TT} \), respectively. Each multipole \( \ell_i \) is mapped to redshift as:
	\begin{equation}
		z_i = \frac{1100}{\ell_i + \epsilon}, \quad \epsilon \ll 1
	\end{equation}
	
	We normalize each amplitude:
	\begin{equation}
		A_i = \frac{D_{\ell_i}^{TT} - \min(D)}{\max(D) - \min(D)}
	\end{equation}
	Then define:
	\begin{align}
		\mu(z) &= \sum_{i \in \text{peaks}} A_i \exp\left[-\frac{(z - z_i)^2}{2\lambda^2}\right] \\
		\nu(z) &= \sum_{j \in \text{troughs}} A_j \exp\left[-\frac{(z - z_j)^2}{2\lambda^2}\right] \\
		\phi(z) &= \mu(z) - \nu(z) \\
		\kappa(z) &= \mu(z) \cdot \frac{d\nu(z)}{dz}
	\end{align}
	The fields \( \mu(z) \) and \( \nu(z) \) are interpreted as coherence burst sources and coherence sink wells, respectively. The total coherence field \( \phi(z) \) encodes the net memory available to influence spacetime structure at each redshift.
	
	\section{Field-Theoretic Dynamics}
	We define the Lagrangian density:
	\begin{equation}
		\mathcal{L}_\phi = \frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{d\phi}{dz}\right)^2 - V(\phi) + \gamma \kappa(z) \phi(z)
	\end{equation}
	
	With potentials:
	\begin{itemize}
		\item Harmonic: \( V(\phi) = \frac{1}{2} m^2 \phi^2 \)
		\item Symmetry-breaking: \( V(\phi) = \lambda(\phi^2 - \phi_0^2)^2 \)
	\end{itemize}
	
	The corresponding Euler--Lagrange equation becomes:
	\begin{equation}
		\frac{d^2 \phi}{dz^2} + \frac{dV}{d\phi} = \gamma \frac{d\kappa(z)}{dz}
	\end{equation}
	This equation governs the redshift evolution of the total coherence field \( \phi(z) \), driven by the derivative of the echo kernel \( \kappa(z) \), representing feedback from gravitational wells activated by coherence bursts.
	
