	\section{Theoretical Role of $\phi(z)$ in Structure Formation}
	
	In the QCT framework, the field $\phi(z)$ represents the redshift-dependent density of quantum coherence encoded in the fabric of spacetime. It is constructed from the difference between coherence bursts $\mu(z)$ and coherence wells $\nu(z)$, derived directly from harmonic structures in the CMB temperature spectrum.
	
	\begin{itemize}
		\item Peaks in $\phi(z)$ correspond to coherence eruptions—regions where early-universe quantum memory amplifies expansion or resists gravitational collapse.
		\item Troughs in $\phi(z)$ mark coherence sinks—stable gravitational anchors that correlate with large-scale structures like galaxy clusters and void boundaries.
	\end{itemize}
	
	This field plays a dual role:
	\begin{itemize}
		\item It replaces cold dark matter by explaining clustering and gravitational effects through memory retention and coherence field gradients.
