	As such, $\phi(z)$ functions as a unified structural field, removing the need for non-observable entities and offering an empirically grounded, CMB-derived alternative to $\Lambda$CDM.
	
	Thus, \( \phi(z) \) replaces the need for cold dark matter (by sourcing structure via quantum coherence retention) and the cosmological constant (by modulating expansion pressure via coherence burst decay). This unification reduces reliance on external energy components and offers a testable explanation rooted entirely in observable CMB physics.


	\section*{Data Cleaning and Preprocessing Rationale}
	
	To ensure that the Quantum Coherence Theory (QCT) model was evaluated on consistent, physically meaningful inputs, we performed light-touch but principled cleaning on each dataset. Our goal was to remove artifacts, invalid values, and ambiguous entries while preserving the raw structural information each dataset provides. Below we outline the cleaning steps and their justification.
	
	\subsection*{CMB TT Spectrum (Planck)}
	\textbf{File:} \texttt{COM\_PowerSpect\_CMB-TT-full\_R3.01.txt} \\
	\textbf{Cleaning Method:}
	\begin{itemize}
		\item Retained only the first two columns: multipole index \( \ell \) and temperature power \( D_\ell^{TT} \)
		\item Filtered rows where \( \ell \leq 0 \) or \( D_\ell^{TT} \leq 0 \)
		\item Removed duplicate \( \ell \) values
	\end{itemize}
	\textbf{Rationale:} Negative or zero values would break log-scaling and normalization. Since QCT coherence fields are derived from peak/trough detection in this spectrum, we ensured continuity and monotonicity by removing duplicates and non-physical entries.
	
	\subsection*{Pantheon+ Supernovae}
	\textbf{File:} \texttt{hlsp\_ps1cosmo\_panstarrs\_gpc1\_all\_multi\_v1\_snparams.txt} \\
	\textbf{Cleaning Method:}
	\begin{itemize}
		\item Extracted only supernovae with positive redshift \( z > 0 \)
		\item Used columns: redshift \( z \), distance modulus \( m_B \), and its error \( \sigma_{m_B} \)
		\item Dropped all other auxiliary metadata
	\end{itemize}
	\textbf{Rationale:} Distance modulus becomes undefined or unphysical at \( z = 0 \), and zero/negative redshifts are cosmologically invalid. Unused host or SNID metadata was excluded to simplify reproducibility.
	
	\subsection*{KiDS Weak Lensing}
	\textbf{File:} \texttt{KiDS\_XIP.txt} \\
	\textbf{Cleaning Method:}
	\begin{itemize}
		\item Extracted angular separation \( \theta \) (in arcminutes) and \( \xi_+ \) (two-point shear correlation)
		\item Filtered non-numeric or NaN entries
		\item Converted angular separation to pseudo-redshift \( z \approx 1 / (1 + \theta) \) for alignment with QCT fields
	\end{itemize}
	\textbf{Rationale:} KiDS measurements are given in angular space. Since QCT fields are defined in redshift space, we employed an approximate mapping to align the data structurally while preserving the relative scale of coherence.
	
	\subsection*{DR9Q Quasar Catalog}
	\textbf{File:} \texttt{DR9Q.dat} \\
	\textbf{Cleaning Method:}
	\begin{itemize}
		\item Parsed redshifts from column 8 (confirmed manually)
		\item Filtered out values \( z \leq 0 \) or \( z > 6 \)
		\item Created a redshift histogram (normalized) with 100 bins between \( z = 0.1 \) and \( z = 5 \)
	\end{itemize}
	\textbf{Rationale:} Only redshift values were needed to compare to QCT's burst field \( \mu(z) \). Histogramming was used to reveal structure while remaining agnostic to completeness or absolute number counts.
	
	\subsection*{GWTC Merger Events}
	\textbf{File:} \texttt{GWTC\_Data.txt} \\
	\textbf{Cleaning Method:}
	\begin{itemize}
		\item Extracted redshift column and removed non-numeric values
		\item Filtered out \( z \leq 0 \) or extreme outliers
		\item Constructed a redshift histogram to match resolution of QCT fields
	\end{itemize}
	\textbf{Rationale:} Gravitational wave merger events are sparse and concentrated at low redshift. We filtered conservatively to remove catalog artifacts while preserving signal.
	
	\subsection*{BAO Power Spectrum (Beutler DR12)}
	\textbf{File:} \texttt{Beutleretal\_pk\_monopole\_DR12\_NGC\_z1\_postrecon\_120.dat} \\
	\textbf{Cleaning Method:}
	\begin{itemize}
		\item Skipped header and extracted columns: \( k_{\min} \), \( k_{\max} \), \( P(k) \), \( \sigma_{P(k)} \)
		\item Mapped each \( k \) bin center to approximate redshift \( z = 0.3 / k \)
		\item Filtered out values with remapped \( z \) outside [0.1, 5]
	\end{itemize}
	\textbf{Rationale:} BAO is defined in Fourier space; QCT is defined in redshift. A phenomenological remapping allowed for structural comparison without converting units. The range clipping ensures relevance to observable structure formation epochs.
	
	\subsection*{Cohesion}
	Each dataset was cleaned independently using a minimal rule set to ensure **unit consistency**, **physical validity**, and **statistical reproducibility**. No smoothing, fitting, or interpolation was applied to datasets before comparison. Normalization was used only post-hoc to allow visual and RMS-based structure alignment with coherence fields derived from the CMB.
	
	\section{Normalization Justification and Residual Integrity}
	Due to the unit and scale differences across datasets, normalization was applied using min-max scaling per dataset. This enables fair shape comparison without altering the coherence fields. Importantly:
	\begin{itemize}
		\item Fields were \textit{not} tuned to data
		\item Dataset-to-field mappings were fixed based on physical justification
		\item Correlation metrics (Pearson \( r \), Spearman \( \rho \)) confirmed alignment beyond RMS
	\end{itemize}
